summaries.title: Summary 308.1
summaries.summaryText: Maria described difficulty understanding financial aid processes and navigating academic advising resources. She relied heavily on peer networks and informal guidance, noting that the institutional language often assumed prior family familiarity with college systems. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Summary 308.2
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Summary 308.3
summaries.summaryText: She emphasized how few Black women were visible in faculty and leadership roles, describing representation as both motivating and emotionally taxing. Her NSBE involvement offered vital affirmation and a platform to advocate for equity. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Summary 308.4
summaries.summaryText: As a first-generation student, Daniel’s parents provided emotional encouragement but limited academic guidance. Their sacrifices motivated him, though he expressed anxiety about failing to meet expectations. [Part 2/4]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge.

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Maria’s sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 3]

quotes.quoteText: I realized I had access to engineering summer camps that most of my friends never even heard of — that’s when privilege clicked for me. [Context 1]
Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 2]
If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, that’s what good leadership looks like. [Context 1]
I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship — it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 1]
At first I thought I wasn’t smart enough, but then I realized everyone’s struggling; we just don’t talk about it. [Context 4]
Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 3]
Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethan’s reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 1]
